    "body": "Luckily I rarely use this machine, it's my partner's laptop, so I have just left it in the state it is in with this problem. It is still in a pristine configuration state, brand new install of arch on a framework, fresh install of ZSH, no possibilities of other config problems. Is there no other information I can acquire for this project that may help diagnose the problem before the time comes when I need to actually use this machine and have a working shell prompt? Some stuff that comes to mind:\n\n```\nHostname% starship prompt\n\n󰣇 scott  ~   07:13  \n %                                                                                                           \nHostname% # That's correct ^\nHostname% export PROMPT='test: '\ntest: echo it works\nit works\ntest: exit\n```\nanother thing\n```\nHostname% cat .zshrc\nexport STARSHIP_CONFIG=$HOME/.config/starship.toml\neval $(starship init zsh)\nHostname% eval $(starship init zsh)\nHostname% setopt promptsubst\nHostname% starship init zsh | grep '^PROMPT'\nPROMPT='$('/usr/bin/starship' prompt --terminal-width=\"$COLUMNS\" --keymap=\"${KEYMAP:-}\" --status=\"$STARSHIP_CMD_STATUS\" --pipestatus=\"${STARSHIP_PIPE_STATUS[*]}\" --cmd-duration=\"${STARSHIP_DURATION:-}\" --jobs=\"$STARSHIP_JOBS_COUNT\")'\nPROMPT2=\"$(/usr/bin/starship prompt --continuation)\"\nHostname% PROMPT='$('/usr/bin/starship' prompt --terminal-width=\"$COLUMNS\" --keymap=\"${KEYMAP:-}\" --status=\"$STARSHIP_CMD_STATUS\" --pipestatus=\"${STARSHIP_PIPE_STATUS[*]}\" --cmd-duration=\"${STARSHIP_DURATION:-}\" --jobs=\"$STARSHIP_JOBS_COUNT\")'\nPROMPT2=\"$(/usr/bin/starship prompt --continuation)\"\n\n󰣇 scott  ~   07:22  \n  # the prompt appears correctly! \n```\n\n(to be clear I copy-pasted the lines which set the prompt variables out of the file and executed them manually)\n\nthis leads me to wonder, a workaround perhaps?\n\n```\nHostname% starship init zsh > .config/starship-init.sh\nHostname% vim .zshrc   \nHostname% cat .zshrc\n# export STARSHIP_CONFIG=$HOME/.config/starship.toml\n# eval $(starship init zsh)\n\nsource $HOME/.config/starship-init.sh\nHostname% source .zshrc\n󰣇 scott  ~   07:44  \n  \n```\n\nand there we go. So it's definitely something specifically wrong with `eval`ing the init. Any tips on how to turn this workaround into a fix?\n\nThe disadvantage of this workaround is obviously that it wouldn't reflect changes to `starship.toml` until you re-run the command that writes the script to the file",
    "author_association": "NONE",
